events.description: Roman emperor Nerva is forced by the Praetorian Guard to adopt general Marcus Ulpius Trajanus as his heir and successor.
events.html: • 97 – Roman emperor Nerva is forced by the Praetorian Guard to adopt general Marcus Ulpius Trajanus as his heir and successor.

events.description: Maxentius is proclaimed Roman emperor.
events.html: • 306 – Maxentius is proclaimed Roman emperor.

events.description: Constantine I defeats Maxentius, becoming the sole Roman emperor in the West.
events.html: • 312 – Constantine I defeats Maxentius, becoming the sole Roman emperor in the West.

events.description: The Byzantine Empire recovers Antioch from Arab rule.
events.html: • 969 – The Byzantine Empire recovers Antioch from Arab rule.

events.description: The lower town of Smyrna is captured by Latin Christians in response to Aydınid piracy during the Smyrniote crusades.
events.html: • 1344 – The lower town of Smyrna is captured by Latin Christians in response to Aydınid piracy during the Smyrniote crusades.[1]

events.description: Beijing is officially designated the capital of the Ming dynasty when the Forbidden City is completed.
events.html: • 1420 – Beijing is officially designated the capital of the Ming dynasty when the Forbidden City is completed.

events.description: Christian I is crowned king of Denmark.
events.html: • 1449 – Christian I is crowned king of Denmark.

events.description: Ladislaus the Posthumous is crowned king of Bohemia in Prague.
events.html: • 1453 – Ladislaus the Posthumous is crowned king of Bohemia in Prague.

events.description: Christopher Columbus lands in Cuba on his first voyage to the New World, surmising that it is Japan.
events.html: • 1492 – Christopher Columbus lands in Cuba on his first voyage to the New World, surmising that it is Japan.[2]

events.description: Second Ottoman–Mamluk War: Mamluks fail to stop the Ottoman advance towards Egypt at the Battle of Yaunis Khan.
events.html: • 1516 – Second Ottoman–Mamluk War: Mamluks fail to stop the Ottoman advance towards Egypt at the Battle of Yaunis Khan.

events.description: Ferdinand Magellan reaches the Pacific Ocean.
events.html: • 1520 – Ferdinand Magellan reaches the Pacific Ocean.[3]

events.description: Abyssinian–Adal war: The Adal Sultanate seizes southern Ethiopia.
events.html: • 1531 – Abyssinian–Adal war: The Adal Sultanate seizes southern Ethiopia.

events.description: The Universidad Santo Tomás de Aquino is founded in what is now the Dominican Republic.
events.html: • 1538 – The Universidad Santo Tomás de Aquino is founded in what is now the Dominican Republic.

events.description: French Wars of Religion: The Siege of La Rochelle ends with the surrender of the Huguenots after fourteen months.
events.html: • 1628 – French Wars of Religion: The Siege of La Rochelle ends with the surrender of the Huguenots after fourteen months.

events.description: The Massachusetts Bay Colony votes to establish a theological college, which would later become Harvard University.
events.html: • 1636 – The Massachusetts Bay Colony votes to establish a theological college, which would later become Harvard University.

events.description: The Treaty of Ripon is signed, ending the hostilities of the Second Bishops’ War.
events.html: • 1640 – The Treaty of Ripon is signed, ending the hostilities of the Second Bishops’ War.[4]

events.description: The Duke of York and Albany's Maritime Regiment of Foot, later to be known as the Royal Marines, is established.
events.html: • 1664 – The Duke of York and Albany's Maritime Regiment of Foot, later to be known as the Royal Marines, is established.

events.description: The 1707 Hōei earthquake causes more than 5,000 deaths in Japan.
events.html: • 1707 – The 1707 Hōei earthquake causes more than 5,000 deaths in Japan.

events.description: The novel Gulliver's Travels written by Jonathan Swift is published.
events.html: • 1726 – The novel Gulliver's Travels written by Jonathan Swift is published.

events.description: American Revolutionary War: British troops attack and capture Chatterton Hill from the Continental Army.
events.html: • 1776 – American Revolutionary War: British troops attack and capture Chatterton Hill from the Continental Army.

events.description: The Pinjarra massacre occurs in the Swan River Colony. An estimated 30 Noongar people are killed by British colonists.
events.html: • 1834 – The Pinjarra massacre occurs in the Swan River Colony. An estimated 30 Noongar people are killed by British colonists.

events.description: The United Tribes of New Zealand are established with the signature of the Declaration of Independence.
events.html: • 1835 – The United Tribes of New Zealand are established with the signature of the Declaration of Independence.

entities.name: Declaration of the Independence of New Zealand

events.description: American Civil War: A Union attack on the Confederate capital of Richmond is repulsed.
events.html: • 1864 – American Civil War: A Union attack on the Confederate capital of Richmond is repulsed.

entities.name: Battle of Fair Oaks & Darbytown Road

events.description: US president Grover Cleveland dedicates the Statue of Liberty.
events.html: • 1886 – US president Grover Cleveland dedicates the Statue of Liberty.

events.description: The Mino–Owari earthquake, the largest inland earthquake in Japan's history, occurs.
events.html: • 1891 – The Mino–Owari earthquake, the largest inland earthquake in Japan's history, occurs.

events.description: Pyotr Tchaikovsky's Symphony No. 6 in B Minor, Pathétique receives its première performance only nine days before the composer's death.
events.html: • 1893 – Pyotr Tchaikovsky's Symphony No. 6 in B Minor, Pathétique receives its première performance only nine days before the composer's death.

events.description: World War I: A new Polish government in western Galicia is established, triggering the Polish–Ukrainian War.
events.html: • 1918 – World War I: A new Polish government in western Galicia is established, triggering the Polish–Ukrainian War.

events.description: World War I: Czech politicians peacefully take over the city of Prague, thus establishing the First Czechoslovak Republic.
events.html: • 1918 – World War I: Czech politicians peacefully take over the city of Prague, thus establishing the First Czechoslovak Republic.[5]

events.description: The U.S. Congress passes the Volstead Act over President Woodrow Wilson's veto, paving the way for Prohibition to begin the following January.
events.html: • 1919 – The U.S. Congress passes the Volstead Act over President Woodrow Wilson's veto, paving the way for Prohibition to begin the following January.

events.description: Italian fascists led by Benito Mussolini march on Rome and take over the Italian government.
events.html: • 1922 – Italian fascists led by Benito Mussolini march on Rome and take over the Italian government.

events.description: Indonesia Raya, now the national anthem of Indonesia, is first played during the Second Indonesian Youth Congress.
events.html: • 1928 – Indonesia Raya, now the national anthem of Indonesia, is first played during the Second Indonesian Youth Congress.[6]

events.description: World War II: Greece rejects Italy's ultimatum. Italy invades Greece through Albania a few hours later.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: Greece rejects Italy's ultimatum. Italy invades Greece through Albania a few hours later.

events.description: The Alaska Highway first connects Alaska to the North American railway network at Dawson Creek in Canada.
events.html: • 1942 – The Alaska Highway first connects Alaska to the North American railway network at Dawson Creek in Canada.

events.description: Paul Hermann Müller is awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his discovery of the insecticidal properties of DDT.
events.html: • 1948 – Paul Hermann Müller is awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his discovery of the insecticidal properties of DDT.

events.description: Ecological disaster in Donora, Pennsylvania.
events.html: • 1948 – Ecological disaster in Donora, Pennsylvania.[7]

events.description: An Air France Lockheed Constellation crashes in the Azores, killing all 48 people on board.
events.html: • 1949 – An Air France Lockheed Constellation crashes in the Azores, killing all 48 people on board.

events.description: Hungarian Revolution: A de facto ceasefire comes into effect between armed revolutionaries and Soviet troops, who begin to withdraw from Budapest. Communist officials and facilities come under attack by revolutionaries.
events.html: • 1956 – Hungarian Revolution: A de facto ceasefire comes into effect between armed revolutionaries and Soviet troops, who begin to withdraw from Budapest. Communist officials and facilities come under attack by revolutionaries.

events.description: Aeroflot Flight 136 crashes near Krasnoyarsk, killing 19.
events.html: • 1954 – Aeroflot Flight 136 crashes near Krasnoyarsk, killing 19.[8]

events.description: John XXIII is elected Pope.
events.html: • 1958 – John XXIII is elected Pope.

events.description: The Cuban Missile Crisis ends and Premier Nikita Khrushchev orders the removal of Soviet missiles from Cuba.
events.html: • 1962 – The Cuban Missile Crisis ends and Premier Nikita Khrushchev orders the removal of Soviet missiles from Cuba.

events.description: Pope Paul VI promulgates Nostra aetate, by which the Roman Catholic Church officially recognizes the legitimacy of non-Christian faiths.
events.html: • 1965 – Pope Paul VI promulgates Nostra aetate, by which the Roman Catholic Church officially recognizes the legitimacy of non-Christian faiths.

events.description: Prospero becomes the only British satellite to be launched by a British rocket.
events.html: • 1971 – Prospero becomes the only British satellite to be launched by a British rocket.

events.description: The Spanish general election begins fourteen years of rule by the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party.
events.html: • 1982 – The Spanish general election begins fourteen years of rule by the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party.

events.description: Georgia holds its only free election under Soviet rule.
events.html: • 1990 – Georgia holds its only free election under Soviet rule.

events.description: The Baku Metro fire sees 289 people killed and 270 injured.
events.html: • 1995 – The Baku Metro fire sees 289 people killed and 270 injured.

events.description: A funeral service takes place at the Bykivnia graves for Ukrainians who were killed by the Soviet secret police.
events.html: • 2006 – A funeral service takes place at the Bykivnia graves for Ukrainians who were killed by the Soviet secret police.

events.description: Cristina Fernández de Kirchner becomes the first directly elected female President of Argentina.
events.html: • 2007 – Cristina Fernández de Kirchner becomes the first directly elected female President of Argentina.

events.description: The 28 October 2009 Peshawar bombing kills 117 and wounds 213.
events.html: • 2009 – The 28 October 2009 Peshawar bombing kills 117 and wounds 213.

events.description: NASA successfully launches the Ares I-X mission, the only rocket launch for its short-lived Constellation program.
events.html: • 2009 – NASA successfully launches the Ares I-X mission, the only rocket launch for its short-lived Constellation program.

events.description: US President Barack Obama signs the Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act.
events.html: • 2009 – US President Barack Obama signs the Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act.[9]

entities.name: Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act

events.description: Five people are killed and 38 are injured after a car crashes into barriers at Tiananmen Square in China.
events.html: • 2013 – Five people are killed and 38 are injured after a car crashes into barriers at Tiananmen Square in China.

events.description: A rocket carrying NASA's Cygnus CRS Orb-3 resupply mission to the International Space Station explodes seconds after taking off from the Mid-Atlantic Regional Spaceport in Wallops Island, Virginia.
events.html: • 2014 – A rocket carrying NASA's Cygnus CRS Orb-3 resupply mission to the International Space Station explodes seconds after taking off from the Mid-Atlantic Regional Spaceport in Wallops Island, Virginia.

events.description: Jair Bolsonaro is elected president of Brazil with 57 million votes, with Workers' Party candidate Fernando Haddad as the runner-up. It is the first time in 16 years that a Workers' Party candidate is not elected president.
events.html: • 2018 – Jair Bolsonaro is elected president of Brazil with 57 million votes, with Workers' Party candidate Fernando Haddad as the runner-up. It is the first time in 16 years that a Workers' Party candidate is not elected president.

events.description: The 2023 Rugby World Cup final is held at the Stade de France in Saint-Denis, France. It saw South Africa defeat New Zealand 11 to 12, claiming their fourth Webb Ellis Cup, becoming the first nation to do so.
events.html: • 2023 – The 2023 Rugby World Cup final is held at the Stade de France in Saint-Denis, France. It saw South Africa defeat New Zealand 11 to 12, claiming their fourth Webb Ellis Cup, becoming the first nation to do so.[10]
